# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: lattice-boltzmann
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:lattice-boltzmann/bhatnagar-gross-krook-operator] The **Bhatnagar–Gross–Krook operator** (abbreviated **BGK operator**) term refers to a collision operator used in the Boltzmann equation and in the lattice Boltzmann method, a computational fluid dynamics technique.
[src:lattice-boltzmann/bhatnagar-gross-krook-operator] where $n_{i}^{\text{eq}}$ is a local equilibrium value for the population of particles in the direction of link $\mathbf {e} _{i}$ .
[src:lattice-boltzmann/bhatnagar-gross-krook-operator] The term $\tau$ is a relaxation time and related to the viscosity.
[src:lattice-boltzmann/bhatnagar-gross-krook-operator] Gross, and Max Krook, the three scientists who introduced it in an article in *Physical Review* in 1954.
[src:lattice-boltzmann/boltzmann-equation] The **Boltzmann equation** or **Boltzmann transport equation** (**BTE**) describes the statistical behaviour of a thermodynamic system not in a state of equilibrium; it was devised by Ludwig Boltzmann in 1872.
[src:lattice-boltzmann/boltzmann-equation] The classic example of such a system is a fluid with temperature gradients in space causing heat to flow from hotter regions to colder ones, by the random but biased transport of the particles making up that fluid.
[src:lattice-boltzmann/boltzmann-equation] In the modern literature the term Boltzmann equation is often used in a more general sense, referring to any kinetic equation that describes the change of a macroscopic quantity in a thermodynamic system, such as energy, charge or particle number.
[src:lattice-boltzmann/boltzmann-equation] The Boltzmann equation can be used to determine how physical quantities change, such as heat energy and momentum, when a fluid is in transport.
[src:lattice-boltzmann/boltzmann-equation] One may also derive other properties characteristic to fluids such as viscosity, thermal conductivity, and electrical conductivity (by treating the charge carriers in a material as a gas).
[src:lattice-boltzmann/boltzmann-equation] The equation is a nonlinear integro-differential equation, and the unknown function in the equation is a probability density function in six-dimensional space of a particle position and momentum.
[src:lattice-boltzmann/boltzmann-equation] The problem of existence and uniqueness of solutions is still not fully resolved, but some recent results are quite promising.
[src:lattice-boltzmann/boltzmann-equation] The set of all possible positions **r** and momenta **p** is called the phase space of the system; in other words a set of three coordinates for each position coordinate *x, y, z*, and three more for each momentum component *px*, *py*, *pz*.
[src:lattice-boltzmann/boltzmann-equation] The entire space is 6-dimensional: a point in this space is (**r**, **p**) = (*x, y, z, px, py, pz*), and each coordinate is parameterized by time *t*.
[src:lattice-boltzmann/boltzmann-equation] While *f* is associated with a number of particles, the phase space is for one-particle (not all of them, which is usually the case with deterministic many-body systems), since only one **r** and **p** is in question.
[src:lattice-boltzmann/boltzmann-equation] It is assumed the particles in the system are identical (so each has an identical mass m).
[src:lattice-boltzmann/boltzmann-equation] For a mixture of more than one chemical species, one distribution is needed for each, see below.
[src:lattice-boltzmann/boltzmann-equation] where the "force" term corresponds to the forces exerted on the particles by an external influence (not by the particles themselves), the "diff" term represents the diffusion of particles, and "coll" is the collision term – accounting for the forces acting between particles in collisions.
[src:lattice-boltzmann/boltzmann-equation] Expressions for each term on the right side are provided below.
[src:lattice-boltzmann/boltzmann-equation] Note that some authors use the particle velocity **v** instead of momentum **p**; they are related in the definition of momentum by **p** = *m***v**.
[src:lattice-boltzmann/boltzmann-equation] Consider particles described by *f*, each experiencing an *external* force **F** not due to other particles (see the collision term for the latter treatment).
[src:lattice-boltzmann/boltzmann-equation] Suppose at time t some number of particles all have position **r** within element $d^{3}\mathbf {r}$ and momentum **p** within $d^{3}\mathbf {p}$ .
[src:lattice-boltzmann/boltzmann-equation] If a force **F** instantly acts on each particle, then at time *t* + Δ*t* their position will be $\mathbf {r} +\Delta \mathbf {r} =\mathbf {r} +{\frac {\mathbf {p} }{m}}\,\Delta t$ and momentum $\mathbf {p} +\Delta \mathbf {p} =\mathbf {p} +\mathbf {F} \Delta t$ .
[src:lattice-boltzmann/boltzmann-equation] Note that we have used the fact that the phase space volume element $d^{3}\mathbf {r} \,d^{3}\mathbf {p}$ is constant, which can be shown using Hamilton's equations (see the discussion under Liouville's theorem).
[src:lattice-boltzmann/boltzmann-equation] where Δ*f* is the *total* change in *f*.
[src:lattice-boltzmann/boltzmann-equation] In this context, **F**(**r**, *t*) is the force field acting on the particles in the fluid, and m is the mass of the particles.
[src:lattice-boltzmann/boltzmann-equation] The term on the right hand side is added to describe the effect of collisions between particles; if it is zero then the particles do not collide.
[src:lattice-boltzmann/boltzmann-equation] The collisionless Boltzmann equation, where individual collisions are replaced with long-range aggregated interactions, e.g.
[src:lattice-boltzmann/boltzmann-equation] Coulomb interactions, is often called the Vlasov equation.
[src:lattice-boltzmann/boltzmann-equation] This equation is more useful than the principal one above, yet still incomplete, since *f* cannot be solved unless the collision term in *f* is known.
[src:lattice-boltzmann/boltzmann-equation] This term cannot be found as easily or generally as the others – it is a statistical term representing the particle collisions, and requires knowledge of the statistics the particles obey, like the Maxwell–Boltzmann, Fermi–Dirac or Bose–Einstein distributions.
[src:lattice-boltzmann/boltzmann-equation] A key insight applied by Boltzmann was to determine the collision term resulting solely from two-body collisions between particles that are assumed to be uncorrelated prior to the collision.
[src:lattice-boltzmann/boltzmann-equation] This assumption was referred to by Boltzmann as the "*Stosszahlansatz*" and is also known as the "molecular chaos assumption".
[src:lattice-boltzmann/boltzmann-equation] Since much of the challenge in solving the Boltzmann equation originates with the complex collision term, attempts have been made to "model" and simplify the collision term.
[src:lattice-boltzmann/boltzmann-equation] The best known model equation is due to Bhatnagar, Gross and Krook.
[src:lattice-boltzmann/boltzmann-equation] where $\nu$ is the molecular collision frequency, and $f_{0}$ is the local Maxwellian distribution function given the gas temperature at this point in space.
[src:lattice-boltzmann/boltzmann-equation] This is also called "relaxation time approximation".
[src:lattice-boltzmann/boltzmann-equation] and *Iij* is the differential cross-section, as before, between particles *i* and *j*.
[src:lattice-boltzmann/boltzmann-equation] The integration is over the momentum components in the integrand (which are labelled *i* and *j*).
[src:lattice-boltzmann/boltzmann-equation] The sum of integrals describes the entry and exit of particles of species *i* in or out of the phase-space element.
[src:lattice-boltzmann/boltzmann-equation] The Boltzmann equation can be used to derive the fluid dynamic conservation laws for mass, charge, momentum, and energy.
[src:lattice-boltzmann/boltzmann-equation] Since the conservation equations involve tensors, the Einstein summation convention will be used where repeated indices in a product indicate summation over those indices.
[src:lattice-boltzmann/boltzmann-equation] Thus $\mathbf {x} \mapsto x_{i}$ and $\mathbf {p} \mapsto p_{i}=mv_{i}$ , where $v_{i}$ is the particle velocity vector.
[src:lattice-boltzmann/boltzmann-equation] Define $A(p_{i})$ as some function of momentum $p_{i}$ only, whose total value is conserved in a collision.
[src:lattice-boltzmann/boltzmann-equation] Assume also that the force $F_{i}$ is a function of position only, and that *f* is zero for $p_{i}\to \pm \infty$ .
[src:lattice-boltzmann/boltzmann-equation] where the last term is zero, since *A* is conserved in a collision.
[src:lattice-boltzmann/boltzmann-equation] The values of *A* correspond to moments of velocity $v_{i}$ (and momentum $p_{i}$ , as they are linearly dependent).
[src:lattice-boltzmann/boltzmann-equation] where $P_{ij}=\rho \langle (v_{i}-V_{i})(v_{j}-V_{j})\rangle$ is the pressure tensor (the viscous stress tensor plus the hydrostatic pressure).
[src:lattice-boltzmann/boltzmann-equation] It is possible to write down relativistic quantum Boltzmann equations for relativistic quantum systems in which the number of particles is not conserved in collisions.
[src:lattice-boltzmann/boltzmann-equation] This has several applications in physical cosmology, including the formation of the light elements in Big Bang nucleosynthesis, the production of dark matter and baryogenesis.
[src:lattice-boltzmann/boltzmann-equation] It is not a priori clear that the state of a quantum system can be characterized by a classical phase space density *f*.
[src:lattice-boltzmann/boltzmann-equation] However, for a wide class of applications a well-defined generalization of *f* exists which is the solution of an effective Boltzmann equation that can be derived from first principles of quantum field theory.
[src:lattice-boltzmann/boltzmann-equation] The Boltzmann equation is of use in galactic dynamics.
[src:lattice-boltzmann/boltzmann-equation] In physical cosmology the fully covariant approach has been used to study the cosmic microwave background radiation.
[src:lattice-boltzmann/boltzmann-equation] More generically the study of processes in the early universe often attempt to take into account the effects of quantum mechanics and general relativity.
[src:lattice-boltzmann/boltzmann-equation] In the very dense medium formed by the primordial plasma after the Big Bang, particles are continuously created and annihilated.
[src:lattice-boltzmann/boltzmann-equation] In such an environment quantum coherence and the spatial extension of the wavefunction can affect the dynamics, making it questionable whether the classical phase space distribution *f* that appears in the Boltzmann equation is suitable to describe the system.
[src:lattice-boltzmann/boltzmann-equation] In many cases it is, however, possible to derive an effective Boltzmann equation for a generalized distribution function from first principles of quantum field theory.
[src:lattice-boltzmann/boltzmann-equation] This includes the formation of the light elements in Big Bang nucleosynthesis, the production of dark matter and baryogenesis.
[src:lattice-boltzmann/boltzmann-equation] Exact solutions to the Boltzmann equations have been proven to exist in some cases; this analytical approach provides insight, but is not generally usable in practical problems.
[src:lattice-boltzmann/boltzmann-equation] Assuming a specific inverse power law between interacting particles, fully closed-form solutions to boundary value problems involving gross, spatially homogenous rates of deformation can be found and studied analytically.
[src:lattice-boltzmann/boltzmann-equation] Instead, numerical methods (including finite elements and lattice Boltzmann methods) are generally used to find approximate solutions to the various forms of the Boltzmann equation.
[src:lattice-boltzmann/boltzmann-equation] Example applications range from hypersonic aerodynamics in rarefied gas flows to plasma flows.
[src:lattice-boltzmann/boltzmann-equation] An application of the Boltzmann equation in electrodynamics is the calculation of the electrical conductivity - the result is in leading order identical with the semiclassical result.
[src:lattice-boltzmann/boltzmann-equation] Close to local equilibrium, solution of the Boltzmann equation can be represented by an asymptotic expansion in powers of Knudsen number (the Chapman–Enskog expansion).
[src:lattice-boltzmann/boltzmann-equation] The first two terms of this expansion give the Euler equations and the Navier–Stokes equations.
[src:lattice-boltzmann/boltzmann-equation] The problem of developing mathematically the limiting processes, which lead from the atomistic view (represented by Boltzmann's equation) to the laws of motion of continua, is an important part of Hilbert's sixth problem.
[src:lattice-boltzmann/boltzmann-equation] The Boltzmann equation is valid only under several assumptions.
[src:lattice-boltzmann/boltzmann-equation] For instance, the particles are assumed to be pointlike, i.e. without having a finite size.
[src:lattice-boltzmann/boltzmann-equation] There exists a generalization of the Boltzmann equation that is called the Enskog equation.
[src:lattice-boltzmann/boltzmann-equation] The collision term is modified in Enskog equations such that particles have a finite size, for example they can be modelled as spheres having a fixed radius.
[src:lattice-boltzmann/boltzmann-equation] No further degrees of freedom besides translational motion are assumed for the particles.
[src:lattice-boltzmann/boltzmann-equation] If there are internal degrees of freedom, the Boltzmann equation has to be generalized and might possess inelastic collisions.
[src:lattice-boltzmann/boltzmann-equation] Many real fluids like liquids or dense gases have besides the features mentioned above more complex forms of collisions, there will be not only binary, but also ternary and higher order collisions.
[src:lattice-boltzmann/boltzmann-equation] These must be derived by using the BBGKY hierarchy.
[src:lattice-boltzmann/boltzmann-equation] Boltzmann-like equations are also used for the movement of cells.
[src:lattice-boltzmann/boltzmann-equation] Since cells are composite particles that carry internal degrees of freedom, the corresponding generalized Boltzmann equations must have inelastic collision integrals.
[src:lattice-boltzmann/boltzmann-equation] Such equations can describe invasions of cancer cells in tissue, morphogenesis, and chemotaxis-related effects.
[src:lattice-boltzmann/boltzmann-equation] In 2024, Yu Deng, Zaher Hani, and Xiao Ma established a major extension of Lanford's theorem by proving that the Boltzmann equation can be rigorously derived from the Newtonian mechanics of a dilute gas of hard spheres for *practically unlimited time intervals*.
[src:lattice-boltzmann/boltzmann-equation] This result extends the 1975 breakthrough by Oscar Lanford, which was restricted to very short times, and provides a complete microscopic-to-mesoscopic derivation valid as long as the corresponding Boltzmann equation admits a classical solution.
[src:lattice-boltzmann/boltzmann-equation] This work addresses a key aspect of Hilbert's sixth problem by rigorously linking particle-level Newtonian dynamics with the mesoscopic kinetic description, and contributes to understanding how macroscopic irreversibility emerges from time-reversible microscopic laws.
[src:lattice-boltzmann/kinetic-theory-of-gases] The **kinetic theory of gases** is a simple classical model of the thermodynamic behavior of gases.
[src:lattice-boltzmann/kinetic-theory-of-gases] Its introduction allowed many principal concepts of thermodynamics to be established.
[src:lattice-boltzmann/kinetic-theory-of-gases] It treats a gas as composed of numerous particles, too small to be seen with a microscope, in constant, random motion.
[src:lattice-boltzmann/kinetic-theory-of-gases] These particles are now known to be the atoms or molecules of the gas.
[src:lattice-boltzmann/kinetic-theory-of-gases] The basic version of the model describes an ideal gas.
[src:lattice-boltzmann/kinetic-theory-of-gases] It treats the collisions as perfectly elastic and as the only interaction between the particles, which are additionally assumed to be much smaller than their average distance apart.
[src:lattice-boltzmann/kinetic-theory-of-gases] Due to the time reversibility of microscopic dynamics (microscopic reversibility), the kinetic theory is also connected to the principle of detailed balance, in terms of the fluctuation-dissipation theorem (for Brownian motion) and the Onsager reciprocal relations.
[src:lattice-boltzmann/kinetic-theory-of-gases] The theory was historically significant as the first explicit exercise of the ideas of statistical mechanics and it forms the theoretical foundation for rarefied gas dynamics.
[src:lattice-boltzmann/kinetic-theory-of-gases] In about 50 BCE, the Roman philosopher Lucretius proposed that apparently static macroscopic bodies were composed on a small scale of rapidly moving atoms all bouncing off each other.
[src:lattice-boltzmann/kinetic-theory-of-gases] This Epicurean atomistic point of view was rarely considered in the subsequent centuries, when Aristotelian ideas were dominant.
[src:lattice-boltzmann/kinetic-theory-of-gases] One of the first and boldest statements on the relationship between motion of particles and heat was by the English philosopher Francis Bacon in 1620.
[src:lattice-boltzmann/kinetic-theory-of-gases] Boyle also believed that all macroscopic properties, including color, taste and elasticity, are caused by and ultimately consist of nothing but the arrangement and motion of indivisible particles of matter.
[src:lattice-boltzmann/kinetic-theory-of-gases] In a lecture of 1681, Hooke asserted a direct relationship between the temperature of an object and the speed of its internal particles.
[src:lattice-boltzmann/kinetic-theory-of-gases] Also the transfer of heat was explained by the motion of particles.
[src:lattice-boltzmann/kinetic-theory-of-gases] In 1738 Daniel Bernoulli published *Hydrodynamica*, which laid the basis for the kinetic theory of gases.
[src:lattice-boltzmann/kinetic-theory-of-gases] In this work, Bernoulli posited the argument, that gases consist of great numbers of molecules moving in all directions, that their impact on a surface causes the pressure of the gas, and that their average kinetic energy determines the temperature of the gas.
[src:lattice-boltzmann/kinetic-theory-of-gases] The theory was not immediately accepted, in part because conservation of energy had not yet been established, and it was not obvious to physicists how the collisions between molecules could be perfectly elastic.
[src:lattice-boltzmann/kinetic-theory-of-gases] Pioneers of the kinetic theory, whose work was also largely neglected by their contemporaries, were Mikhail Lomonosov (1747), Georges-Louis Le Sage (ca.
[src:lattice-boltzmann/kinetic-theory-of-gases] 1780, published 1818), John Herapath (1816) and John James Waterston (1843), which connected their research with the development of mechanical explanations of gravitation.
[src:lattice-boltzmann/kinetic-theory-of-gases] In 1856 August Krönig created a simple gas-kinetic model, which only considered the translational motion of the particles.
[src:lattice-boltzmann/kinetic-theory-of-gases] In 1857 Rudolf Clausius developed a similar, but more sophisticated version of the theory, which included translational and, contrary to Krönig, also rotational and vibrational molecular motions.
[src:lattice-boltzmann/kinetic-theory-of-gases] In this same work he introduced the concept of mean free path of a particle.
[src:lattice-boltzmann/kinetic-theory-of-gases] In 1859, after reading a paper about the diffusion of molecules by Clausius, Scottish physicist James Clerk Maxwell formulated the Maxwell distribution of molecular velocities, which gave the proportion of molecules having a certain velocity in a specific range.
[src:lattice-boltzmann/kinetic-theory-of-gases] This was the first-ever statistical law in physics.
[src:lattice-boltzmann/kinetic-theory-of-gases] Maxwell also gave the first mechanical argument that molecular collisions entail an equalization of temperatures and hence a tendency towards equilibrium.
[src:lattice-boltzmann/kinetic-theory-of-gases] The logarithmic connection between entropy and probability was also first stated by Boltzmann.
[src:lattice-boltzmann/kinetic-theory-of-gases] At the beginning of the 20th century, atoms were considered by many physicists to be purely hypothetical constructs, rather than real objects.
[src:lattice-boltzmann/kinetic-theory-of-gases] An important turning point was Albert Einstein's (1905) and Marian Smoluchowski's (1906) papers on Brownian motion, which succeeded in making certain accurate quantitative predictions based on the kinetic theory.
[src:lattice-boltzmann/kinetic-theory-of-gases] Following the development of the Boltzmann equation, a framework for its use in developing transport equations was developed independently by David Enskog and Sydney Chapman in 1917 and 1916.
[src:lattice-boltzmann/kinetic-theory-of-gases] The framework provided a route to prediction of the transport properties of dilute gases, and became known as Chapman–Enskog theory.
[src:lattice-boltzmann/kinetic-theory-of-gases] The framework was gradually expanded throughout the following century, eventually becoming a route to prediction of transport properties in real, dense gases.
[src:lattice-boltzmann/kinetic-theory-of-gases] Thus, the dynamics of particle motion can be treated classically, and the equations of motion are time-reversible.
[src:lattice-boltzmann/kinetic-theory-of-gases] As a simplifying assumption, the particles are usually assumed to have the same mass as one another; however, the theory can be generalized to a mass distribution, with each mass type contributing to the gas properties independently of one another in agreement with Dalton's law of partial pressures.
[src:lattice-boltzmann/kinetic-theory-of-gases] Many of the model's predictions are the same whether or not collisions between particles are included, so they are often neglected as a simplifying assumption in derivations (see below).
[src:lattice-boltzmann/kinetic-theory-of-gases] More modern developments, such as the revised Enskog theory and the extended Bhatnagar–Gross–Krook model, relax one or more of the above assumptions.
[src:lattice-boltzmann/kinetic-theory-of-gases] While theories relaxing the assumptions that the gas particles occupy negligible volume and that collisions are strictly elastic have been successful, it has been shown that relaxing the requirement of interactions being binary and uncorrelated will eventually lead to divergent results.
[src:lattice-boltzmann/kinetic-theory-of-gases] In the kinetic theory of gases, the pressure is assumed to be equal to the force (per unit area) exerted by the individual gas atoms or molecules hitting and rebounding from the gas container's surface.
[src:lattice-boltzmann/kinetic-theory-of-gases] Consider a gas particle traveling at velocity, ${\textstyle v_{i}}$ , along the ${\hat {i}}$ -direction in an enclosed volume with characteristic length, $L_{i}$ , cross-sectional area, $A_{i}$ , and volume, $V=A_{i}L_{i}$ .
[src:lattice-boltzmann/kinetic-theory-of-gases] Now consider a large number, N , of gas particles with random orientation in a three-dimensional volume.
[src:lattice-boltzmann/kinetic-theory-of-gases] This is an important, non-trivial result of the kinetic theory because it relates pressure, a macroscopic property, to the translational kinetic energy of the molecules, which is a microscopic property.
[src:lattice-boltzmann/kinetic-theory-of-gases] The mass density of a gas $\rho$ is expressed through the total mass of gas particles and through volume of this gas: $\rho ={\frac {Nm}{V}}$ .
[src:lattice-boltzmann/kinetic-theory-of-gases] In the limit of small speeds, the expression becomes $P\approx \rho {\overline {v^{2}}}/3$ .
[src:lattice-boltzmann/kinetic-theory-of-gases] Equation (**3**) is one important result of the kinetic theory: *The average molecular kinetic energy is proportional to the ideal gas law's absolute temperature*.
[src:lattice-boltzmann/kinetic-theory-of-gases] Thus, the product of pressure and volume per mole is proportional to the average translational molecular kinetic energy.
[src:lattice-boltzmann/kinetic-theory-of-gases] The equipartition theorem requires that kinetic energy is partitioned equally between all kinetic degrees of freedom, *D*.
[src:lattice-boltzmann/kinetic-theory-of-gases] A monatomic gas is axially symmetric about each spatial axis, so that *D* = 3 comprising translational motion along each axis.
[src:lattice-boltzmann/kinetic-theory-of-gases] A diatomic gas is axially symmetric about only one axis, so that *D* = 5, comprising translational motion along three axes and rotational motion along two axes.
[src:lattice-boltzmann/kinetic-theory-of-gases] A polyatomic gas, like water, is not radially symmetric about any axis, resulting in *D* = 6, comprising 3 translational and 3 rotational degrees of freedom.
[src:lattice-boltzmann/kinetic-theory-of-gases] Therefore, the kinetic energy per kelvin of one mole of monatomic ideal gas (*D* = 3) is $K={\frac {D}{2}}k_{\text{B}}N_{\text{A}}={\frac {3}{2}}R,$ where $N_{\text{A}}$ is the Avogadro constant, and *R* is the ideal gas constant.
[src:lattice-boltzmann/kinetic-theory-of-gases] At higher temperatures (typically thousands of kelvins), vibrational modes become active to provide additional degrees of freedom, creating a temperature-dependence on *D* and the total molecular energy.
[src:lattice-boltzmann/kinetic-theory-of-gases] Quantum statistical mechanics is needed to accurately compute these contributions.
[src:lattice-boltzmann/kinetic-theory-of-gases] Then for a small area $dA$ on the container wall, a particle with speed v at angle $\theta$ from the normal of the area $dA$ , will collide with the area within time interval $dt$ , if it is within the distance $v\,dt$ from the area $dA$ .
[src:lattice-boltzmann/kinetic-theory-of-gases] Therefore, all the particles with speed v at angle $\theta$ from the normal that can reach area $dA$ within time interval $dt$ are contained in the tilted pipe with a height of $v\cos(\theta )dt$ and a volume of $v\cos(\theta )\,dA\,dt$ .
[src:lattice-boltzmann/kinetic-theory-of-gases] This quantity is also known as the "impingement rate" in vacuum physics.
[src:lattice-boltzmann/kinetic-theory-of-gases] Note that to calculate the average speed ${\bar {v}}$ of the Maxwell's velocity distribution, one has to integrate over $v>0$ , $0<\theta <\pi$ , $0<\phi <2\pi$ .
[src:lattice-boltzmann/kinetic-theory-of-gases] The above expression is consistent with Graham's law.
[src:lattice-boltzmann/kinetic-theory-of-gases] The most probable (or mode) speed $v_{\text{p}}$ is 81.6% of the root-mean-square speed $v_{\text{rms}}$ , and the mean (arithmetic mean, or average) speed ${\bar {v}}$ is 92.1% of the rms speed (isotropic distribution of speeds).
[src:lattice-boltzmann/kinetic-theory-of-gases] In kinetic theory of gases, the mean free path is the average distance traveled by a molecule, or a number of molecules per volume, before they make their first collision.
[src:lattice-boltzmann/kinetic-theory-of-gases] Let $\sigma$ be the collision cross section of one molecule colliding with another.
[src:lattice-boltzmann/kinetic-theory-of-gases] As in the previous section, the number density n is defined as the number of molecules per (extensive) volume, or $n=N/V$ .
[src:lattice-boltzmann/kinetic-theory-of-gases] Notice that the unit of the collision cross section per volume $n\sigma$ is reciprocal of length.
[src:lattice-boltzmann/kinetic-theory-of-gases] The kinetic theory of gases deals not only with gases in thermodynamic equilibrium, but also very importantly with gases not in thermodynamic equilibrium.
[src:lattice-boltzmann/kinetic-theory-of-gases] This means using Kinetic Theory to consider what are known as "transport properties", such as viscosity, thermal conductivity, mass diffusivity and thermal diffusion.
[src:lattice-boltzmann/kinetic-theory-of-gases] In its most basic form, kinetic gas theory is only applicable to dilute gases.
[src:lattice-boltzmann/kinetic-theory-of-gases] The extension of kinetic gas theory to dense gas mixtures, Revised Enskog Theory, was developed in 1983–1987 by E.
[src:lattice-boltzmann/kinetic-theory-of-gases] Lòpez de Haro, building on work by H. van Beijeren and M.
[src:lattice-boltzmann/kinetic-theory-of-gases] In books on elementary kinetic theory one can find results for dilute gas modeling that are used in many fields.
[src:lattice-boltzmann/kinetic-theory-of-gases] Derivation of the kinetic model for shear viscosity usually starts by considering a Couette flow where two parallel plates are separated by a gas layer.
[src:lattice-boltzmann/kinetic-theory-of-gases] The upper plate is moving at a constant velocity to the right due to a force *F*.
[src:lattice-boltzmann/kinetic-theory-of-gases] The lower plate is stationary, and an equal and opposite force must therefore be acting on it to keep it at rest.
[src:lattice-boltzmann/kinetic-theory-of-gases] The molecules in the gas layer have a forward velocity component u which increase uniformly with distance y above the lower plate.
[src:lattice-boltzmann/kinetic-theory-of-gases] The non-equilibrium flow is superimposed on a Maxwell-Boltzmann equilibrium distribution of molecular motions.
[src:lattice-boltzmann/kinetic-theory-of-gases] Inside a dilute gas in a Couette flow setup, let $u_{0}$ be the forward velocity of the gas at a horizontal flat layer (labeled as $y=0$ ); $u_{0}$ is along the horizontal direction.
[src:lattice-boltzmann/kinetic-theory-of-gases] These molecules made their last collision at $y=\pm \ell \cos \theta$ , where $\ell$ is the mean free path.
[src:lattice-boltzmann/kinetic-theory-of-gases] Each molecule will contribute a forward momentum of $p_{x}^{\pm }=m\left(u_{0}\pm \ell \cos \theta {\frac {du}{dy}}\right),$ where plus sign applies to molecules from above, and minus sign below.
[src:lattice-boltzmann/kinetic-theory-of-gases] Note that the forward velocity gradient $du/dy$ can be considered to be constant over a distance of mean free path.
[src:lattice-boltzmann/kinetic-theory-of-gases] Maxwell-Boltzmann distribution gives the average (equilibrium) molecular speed as ${\bar {v}}={\frac {2}{\sqrt {\pi }}}v_{p}=2{\sqrt {{\frac {2}{\pi }}{\frac {k_{\mathrm {B} }T}{m}}}}$ where $v_{p}$ is the most probable speed.
[src:lattice-boltzmann/kinetic-theory-of-gases] and insert the velocity in the viscosity equation above.
[src:lattice-boltzmann/kinetic-theory-of-gases] The equation above presupposes that the gas density is low (i.e. the pressure is low).
[src:lattice-boltzmann/kinetic-theory-of-gases] This implies that the transport of momentum through the gas due to the translational motion of molecules is much larger than the transport due to momentum being transferred between molecules during collisions.
[src:lattice-boltzmann/kinetic-theory-of-gases] The transfer of momentum between molecules is explicitly accounted for in Revised Enskog theory, which relaxes the requirement of a gas being dilute.
[src:lattice-boltzmann/kinetic-theory-of-gases] The viscosity equation further presupposes that there is only one type of gas molecules, and that the gas molecules are perfect elastic and hard core particles of spherical shape.
[src:lattice-boltzmann/kinetic-theory-of-gases] The radius r is called collision cross section radius or kinetic radius, and the diameter d is called collision cross section diameter or kinetic diameter of a molecule in a monomolecular gas.
[src:lattice-boltzmann/kinetic-theory-of-gases] There are no simple general relation between the collision cross section and the hard core size of the (fairly spherical) molecule.
[src:lattice-boltzmann/kinetic-theory-of-gases] The relation depends on shape of the potential energy of the molecule.
[src:lattice-boltzmann/kinetic-theory-of-gases] For a real spherical molecule (i.e. a noble gas atom or a reasonably spherical molecule) the interaction potential is more like the Lennard-Jones potential or Morse potential which have a negative part that attracts the other molecule from distances longer than the hard core radius.
[src:lattice-boltzmann/kinetic-theory-of-gases] The radius for zero Lennard-Jones potential may then be used as a rough estimate for the kinetic radius.
[src:lattice-boltzmann/kinetic-theory-of-gases] However, using this estimate will typically lead to an erroneous temperature dependency of the viscosity.
[src:lattice-boltzmann/kinetic-theory-of-gases] For such interaction potentials, significantly more accurate results are obtained by numerical evaluation of the required collision integrals.
[src:lattice-boltzmann/kinetic-theory-of-gases] Consider two parallel plates separated by a gas layer.
[src:lattice-boltzmann/kinetic-theory-of-gases] Both plates have uniform temperatures, and are so massive compared to the gas layer that they can be treated as thermal reservoirs.
[src:lattice-boltzmann/kinetic-theory-of-gases] The upper plate has a higher temperature than the lower plate.
[src:lattice-boltzmann/kinetic-theory-of-gases] The molecules in the gas layer have a molecular kinetic energy $\varepsilon$ which increases uniformly with distance y above the lower plate.
[src:lattice-boltzmann/kinetic-theory-of-gases] The non-equilibrium energy flow is superimposed on a Maxwell-Boltzmann equilibrium distribution of molecular motions.
[src:lattice-boltzmann/kinetic-theory-of-gases] Let $\varepsilon _{0}$ be the molecular kinetic energy of the gas at an imaginary horizontal surface inside the gas layer.
[src:lattice-boltzmann/kinetic-theory-of-gases] Again, plus sign applies to molecules from above, and minus sign below.
[src:lattice-boltzmann/kinetic-theory-of-gases] Note that the temperature gradient $dT/dy$ can be considered to be constant over a distance of mean free path.
[src:lattice-boltzmann/kinetic-theory-of-gases] Note that the energy transfer from above is in the $-y$ direction, and therefore the overall minus sign in the equation.
[src:lattice-boltzmann/kinetic-theory-of-gases] Consider a steady diffusion between two regions of the same gas with perfectly flat and parallel boundaries separated by a layer of the same gas.
[src:lattice-boltzmann/kinetic-theory-of-gases] Both regions have uniform number densities, but the upper region has a higher number density than the lower region.
[src:lattice-boltzmann/kinetic-theory-of-gases] In the steady state, the number density at any point is constant (that is, independent of time).
[src:lattice-boltzmann/kinetic-theory-of-gases] However, the number density n in the layer increases uniformly with distance y above the lower plate.
[src:lattice-boltzmann/kinetic-theory-of-gases] The non-equilibrium molecular flow is superimposed on a Maxwell–Boltzmann equilibrium distribution of molecular motions.
[src:lattice-boltzmann/kinetic-theory-of-gases] Let $n_{0}$ be the number density of the gas at an imaginary horizontal surface inside the layer.
[src:lattice-boltzmann/kinetic-theory-of-gases] Note that the number density gradient $dn/dy$ can be considered to be constant over a distance of mean free path.
[src:lattice-boltzmann/kinetic-theory-of-gases] Note that the molecular transfer from above is in the $-y$ direction, and therefore the overall minus sign in the equation.
[src:lattice-boltzmann/kinetic-theory-of-gases] The corresponding expression obtained from Revised Enskog Theory may be written as $D=\alpha _{D}D_{0}$ where $\alpha _{D}$ is a factor that tends to unity in the limit of infinite dilution, which accounts for excluded volume and the variation chemical potentials with density.
[src:lattice-boltzmann/kinetic-theory-of-gases] The kinetic theory of gases entails that due to the microscopic reversibility of the gas particles' detailed dynamics, the system must obey the principle of detailed balance.
[src:lattice-boltzmann/kinetic-theory-of-gases] Note that the mobility *μ* = *v*d/*F* can be calculated based on the viscosity of the gas; Therefore, the Einstein–Smoluchowski equation also provides a relation between the mass diffusivity and the viscosity of the gas.
[src:lattice-boltzmann/knudsen-number] The **Knudsen number** (**Kn**) is a dimensionless number defined as the ratio of the molecular mean free path length to a representative physical length scale.
[src:lattice-boltzmann/knudsen-number] This length scale could be, for example, the radius of a body in a fluid.
[src:lattice-boltzmann/knudsen-number] The number is named after Danish physicist Martin Knudsen (1871–1949).
[src:lattice-boltzmann/knudsen-number] The Knudsen number helps determine whether statistical mechanics or the continuum mechanics formulation of fluid dynamics should be used to model a situation.
[src:lattice-boltzmann/knudsen-number] If the Knudsen number is near or greater than one, the mean free path of a molecule is comparable to a length scale of the problem, and the continuum assumption of fluid mechanics is no longer a good approximation.
[src:lattice-boltzmann/knudsen-number] In such cases, statistical methods should be used.
[src:lattice-boltzmann/knudsen-number] The representative length scale considered, L , may correspond to various physical traits of a system, but most commonly relates to a *gap length* over which thermal transport or mass transport occurs through a gas phase.
[src:lattice-boltzmann/knudsen-number] This is the case in porous and granular materials, where the thermal transport through a gas phase depends highly on its pressure and the consequent mean free path of molecules in this phase.
[src:lattice-boltzmann/knudsen-number] If the temperature is increased, but the *volume* kept constant, then the Knudsen number (and the mean free path) doesn't change (for an ideal gas).
[src:lattice-boltzmann/knudsen-number] In this case, the density stays the same.
[src:lattice-boltzmann/knudsen-number] If the temperature is increased, and the *pressure* kept constant, then the gas expands and therefore its density decreases.
[src:lattice-boltzmann/knudsen-number] In this case, the mean free path increases and so does the Knudsen number.
[src:lattice-boltzmann/knudsen-number] Hence, it may be helpful to keep in mind that the mean free path (and therefore the Knudsen number) is really dependent on the thermodynamic variable density (proportional to the reciprocal of density), and only indirectly on temperature and pressure.
[src:lattice-boltzmann/knudsen-number] For particle dynamics in the atmosphere, and assuming standard temperature and pressure, i.e.
[src:lattice-boltzmann/knudsen-number] The Knudsen number can be related to the Mach number and the Reynolds number.
[src:lattice-boltzmann/knudsen-number] This regime classification is empirical and problem dependent but has proven useful to adequately model flows.
[src:lattice-boltzmann/knudsen-number] Problems with high Knudsen numbers include the calculation of the motion of a dust particle through the lower atmosphere and the motion of a satellite through the exosphere.
[src:lattice-boltzmann/knudsen-number] One of the most widely used applications for the Knudsen number is in microfluidics and MEMS device design where flows range from continuum to free-molecular.
[src:lattice-boltzmann/knudsen-number] In recent years, it has been applied in other disciplines such as transport in porous media, e.g., petroleum reservoirs.
[src:lattice-boltzmann/knudsen-number] Movements of fluids in situations with a high Knudsen number are said to exhibit Knudsen flow, also called free molecular flow.
[src:lattice-boltzmann/knudsen-number] Airflow around an aircraft such as an airliner has a low Knudsen number, making it firmly in the realm of continuum mechanics.
[src:lattice-boltzmann/knudsen-number] Using the Knudsen number an adjustment for Stokes' law can be used in the Cunningham correction factor, this is a drag force correction due to slip in small particles (i.e.
[src:lattice-boltzmann/knudsen-number] The flow of water through a nozzle will usually be a situation with a low Knudsen number.
[src:lattice-boltzmann/knudsen-number] Mixtures of gases with different molecular masses can be partly separated by sending the mixture through small holes of a thin wall because the numbers of molecules that pass through a hole is proportional to the pressure of the gas and inversely proportional to its molecular mass.
[src:lattice-boltzmann/knudsen-number] The technique has been used to separate isotopic mixtures, such as uranium, using porous membranes.
[src:lattice-boltzmann/knudsen-number] It has also been successfully demonstrated for use in hydrogen production from water.
[src:lattice-boltzmann/knudsen-number] The Knudsen number also plays an important role in thermal conduction in gases.
[src:lattice-boltzmann/knudsen-number] For insulation materials, for example, where gases are contained under low pressure, the Knudsen number should be as high as possible to ensure low thermal conductivity.
[src:lattice-boltzmann/lattice-boltzmann-methods] The **lattice Boltzmann methods (LBM)**, originated from the lattice gas automata (LGA) method (Hardy-Pomeau-Pazzis and Frisch-Hasslacher-Pomeau models), is a class of computational fluid dynamics (CFD) methods for fluid simulation.
[src:lattice-boltzmann/lattice-boltzmann-methods] Instead of solving the Navier–Stokes equations directly, a fluid density on a lattice is simulated with streaming and collision (relaxation) processes.
[src:lattice-boltzmann/lattice-boltzmann-methods] The method is versatile as the model fluid can straightforwardly be made to mimic common fluid behaviour like vapour/liquid coexistence, and so fluid systems such as liquid droplets can be simulated.
[src:lattice-boltzmann/lattice-boltzmann-methods] Also, fluids in complex environments such as porous media can be straightforwardly simulated, whereas with complex boundaries other CFD methods can be hard to work with.
[src:lattice-boltzmann/lattice-boltzmann-methods] Unlike CFD methods that solve the conservation equations of macroscopic properties (i.e., mass, momentum, and energy) numerically, LBM models the fluid consisting of fictive particles, and such particles perform consecutive propagation and collision processes over a discrete lattice.
[src:lattice-boltzmann/lattice-boltzmann-methods] Due to its particulate nature and local dynamics, LBM has several advantages over other conventional CFD methods, especially in dealing with complex boundaries, incorporating microscopic interactions, and parallelization of the algorithm.
[src:lattice-boltzmann/lattice-boltzmann-methods] A different interpretation of the lattice Boltzmann equation is that of a discrete-velocity Boltzmann equation.
[src:lattice-boltzmann/lattice-boltzmann-methods] The numerical methods of solution of the system of partial differential equations then give rise to a discrete map, which can be interpreted as the propagation and collision of fictitious particles.
[src:lattice-boltzmann/lattice-boltzmann-methods] In an algorithm, there are collision and streaming steps.
[src:lattice-boltzmann/lattice-boltzmann-methods] These evolve the density of the fluid $\rho ({\vec {x}},t)$ , for ${\vec {x}}$ the position and t the time.
[src:lattice-boltzmann/lattice-boltzmann-methods] As the fluid is on a lattice, the density has a number of components $f_{i},i=0,\ldots ,a$ equal to the number of lattice vectors connected to each lattice point.
[src:lattice-boltzmann/lattice-boltzmann-methods] As an example, the lattice vectors for a simple lattice used in simulations in two dimensions is shown here.
[src:lattice-boltzmann/lattice-boltzmann-methods] This lattice is usually denoted D2Q9, for two dimensions and nine vectors: four vectors along north, east, south and west, plus four vectors to the corners of a unit square, plus a vector with both components zero.
[src:lattice-boltzmann/lattice-boltzmann-methods] Then, for example vector ${\vec {e}}_{4}=(0,-1)$ , i.e., it points due south and so has no x component but a y component of $-1$ .
[src:lattice-boltzmann/lattice-boltzmann-methods] So one of the nine components of the total density at the central lattice point, $f_{4}({\vec {x}},t)$ , is that part of the fluid at point ${\vec {x}}$ moving due south, at a speed in lattice units of one.
[src:lattice-boltzmann/lattice-boltzmann-methods] The model assumes that the fluid locally relaxes to equilibrium over a characteristic timescale $\tau _{f}$ .
[src:lattice-boltzmann/lattice-boltzmann-methods] This timescale determines the kinematic viscosity, the larger it is, the larger is the kinematic viscosity.
[src:lattice-boltzmann/lattice-boltzmann-methods] As $f_{i}^{\ast }({\vec {x}},t)$ is, by definition, the fluid density at point ${\vec {x}}$ at time t , that is moving at a velocity of ${\vec {e}}_{i}$ per time step, then at the next time step $t+\delta _{t}$ it will have flowed to point ${\vec {x}}+{\vec {e}}_{i}\delta _{t}$ .
[src:lattice-boltzmann/lattice-boltzmann-methods] As with Navier–Stokes based CFD, LBM methods have been successfully coupled with thermal-specific solutions to enable heat transfer (solids-based conduction, convection and radiation) simulation capability.
[src:lattice-boltzmann/lattice-boltzmann-methods] For multiphase/multicomponent models, the interface thickness is usually large and the density ratio across the interface is small when compared with real fluids.
[src:lattice-boltzmann/lattice-boltzmann-methods] Recently this problem has been resolved by Yuan and Schaefer who improved on models by Shan and Chen, Swift, and He, Chen, and Zhang.
[src:lattice-boltzmann/lattice-boltzmann-methods] They were able to reach density ratios of 1000:1 by simply changing the equation of state.
[src:lattice-boltzmann/lattice-boltzmann-methods] It has been proposed to apply Galilean Transformation to overcome the limitation of modelling high-speed fluid flows.
[src:lattice-boltzmann/lattice-boltzmann-methods] LBM originated from the lattice gas automata (LGA) method, which can be considered as a simplified fictitious molecular dynamics model in which space, time, and particle velocities are all discrete.
[src:lattice-boltzmann/lattice-boltzmann-methods] For example, in the 2-dimensional FHP Model each lattice node is connected to its neighbors by 6 lattice velocities on a triangular lattice; there can be either 0 or 1 particles at a lattice node moving with a given lattice velocity.
[src:lattice-boltzmann/lattice-boltzmann-methods] After a time interval, each particle will move to the neighboring node in its direction; this process is called the propagation or streaming step.
[src:lattice-boltzmann/lattice-boltzmann-methods] When more than one particle arrives at the same node from different directions, they collide and change their velocities according to a set of collision rules.
[src:lattice-boltzmann/lattice-boltzmann-methods] Streaming steps and collision steps alternate.
[src:lattice-boltzmann/lattice-boltzmann-methods] Suitable collision rules should conserve the particle number (mass), momentum, and energy before and after the collision.
[src:lattice-boltzmann/lattice-boltzmann-methods] LGA suffer from several innate defects for use in hydrodynamic simulations: lack of Galilean invariance for fast flows, statistical noise and poor Reynolds number scaling with lattice size.
[src:lattice-boltzmann/lattice-boltzmann-methods] LGA are, however, well suited to simplify and extend the reach of reaction diffusion and molecular dynamics models.
[src:lattice-boltzmann/lattice-boltzmann-methods] The main motivation for the transition from LGA to LBM was the desire to remove the statistical noise by replacing the Boolean particle number in a lattice direction with its ensemble average, the so-called density distribution function.
[src:lattice-boltzmann/lattice-boltzmann-methods] Accompanying this replacement, the discrete collision rule is also replaced by a continuous function known as the collision operator.
[src:lattice-boltzmann/lattice-boltzmann-methods] In the LBM development, an important simplification is to approximate the collision operator with the Bhatnagar-Gross-Krook (BGK) relaxation term.
[src:lattice-boltzmann/lattice-boltzmann-methods] This lattice BGK (LBGK) model makes simulations more efficient and allows flexibility of the transport coefficients.
[src:lattice-boltzmann/lattice-boltzmann-methods] On the other hand, it has been shown that the LBM scheme can also be considered as a special discretized form of the continuous Boltzmann equation.
[src:lattice-boltzmann/lattice-boltzmann-methods] From Chapman-Enskog theory, one can recover the governing continuity and Navier–Stokes equations from the LBM algorithm.
[src:lattice-boltzmann/lattice-boltzmann-methods] Lattice Boltzmann models can be operated on a number of different lattices, both cubic and triangular, and with or without rest particles in the discrete distribution function.
[src:lattice-boltzmann/lattice-boltzmann-methods] A popular way of classifying the different methods by lattice is the D*n*Q*m* scheme.
[src:lattice-boltzmann/lattice-boltzmann-methods] Here "D*n*" stands for "*n* dimensions", while "Q*m*" stands for "*m* speeds".
[src:lattice-boltzmann/lattice-boltzmann-methods] For example, D3Q15 is a 3-dimensional lattice Boltzmann model on a cubic grid, with rest particles present.
[src:lattice-boltzmann/lattice-boltzmann-methods] Each node has a crystal shape and can deliver particles to 15 nodes: each of the 6 neighboring nodes that share a surface, the 8 neighboring nodes sharing a corner, and itself.
[src:lattice-boltzmann/lattice-boltzmann-methods] Real quantities as space and time need to be converted to lattice units prior to simulation.
[src:lattice-boltzmann/lattice-boltzmann-methods] Nondimensional quantities, like the Reynolds number, remain the same.
[src:lattice-boltzmann/lattice-boltzmann-methods] In most Lattice Boltzmann simulations $\delta _{x}\,\!$ is the basic unit for lattice spacing, so if the domain of length $L\,\!$ has $N\,\!$ lattice units along its entire length, the space unit is simply defined as $\delta _{x}=L/N\,\!$ .
[src:lattice-boltzmann/lattice-boltzmann-methods] Speeds in lattice Boltzmann simulations are typically given in terms of the speed of sound.
[src:lattice-boltzmann/lattice-boltzmann-methods] The discrete time unit can therefore be given as $\delta _{t}={\frac {\delta _{x}}{C_{s}}}\,\!$ , where the denominator $C_{s}$ is the physical speed of sound.
[src:lattice-boltzmann/lattice-boltzmann-methods] For small-scale flows (such as those seen in porous media mechanics), operating with the true speed of sound can lead to unacceptably short time steps.
[src:lattice-boltzmann/lattice-boltzmann-methods] It is therefore common to raise the lattice Mach number to something much larger than the real Mach number, and compensating for this by raising the viscosity as well in order to preserve the Reynolds number.
[src:lattice-boltzmann/lattice-boltzmann-methods] Simulating multiphase/multicomponent flows has always been a challenge to conventional CFD because of the moving and deformable interfaces.
[src:lattice-boltzmann/lattice-boltzmann-methods] More fundamentally, the interfaces between different phases (liquid and vapor) or components (e.g., oil and water) originate from the specific interactions among fluid molecules.
[src:lattice-boltzmann/lattice-boltzmann-methods] Therefore, it is difficult to implement such microscopic interactions into the macroscopic Navier–Stokes equation.
[src:lattice-boltzmann/lattice-boltzmann-methods] However, in LBM, the particulate kinetics provides a relatively easy and consistent way to incorporate the underlying microscopic interactions by modifying the collision operator.
[src:lattice-boltzmann/lattice-boltzmann-methods] Several LBM multiphase/multicomponent models have been developed.
[src:lattice-boltzmann/lattice-boltzmann-methods] Here phase separations are generated automatically from the particle dynamics and no special treatment is needed to manipulate the interfaces as in traditional CFD methods.
[src:lattice-boltzmann/lattice-boltzmann-methods] Successful applications of multiphase/multicomponent LBM models can be found in various complex fluid systems, including interface instability, bubble/droplet dynamics, wetting on solid surfaces, interfacial slip, and droplet electrohydrodynamic deformations.
[src:lattice-boltzmann/lattice-boltzmann-methods] A lattice Boltzmann model for simulation of gas mixture combustion capable of accommodating significant density variations at low-Mach number regime has been recently proposed.
[src:lattice-boltzmann/lattice-boltzmann-methods] To this respect, it is worth to notice that, since LBM deals with a larger set of fields (as compared to conventional CFD), the simulation of reactive gas mixtures presents some additional challenges in terms of memory demand as far as large detailed combustion mechanisms are concerned.
[src:lattice-boltzmann/lattice-boltzmann-methods] Those issues may be addressed, though, by resorting to systematic model reduction techniques.
[src:lattice-boltzmann/lattice-boltzmann-methods] Currently (2009), a thermal lattice-Boltzmann method (TLBM) falls into one of three categories: the multi-speed approach, the passive scalar approach, and the thermal energy distribution.
[src:lattice-boltzmann/lattice-boltzmann-methods] Starting with the discrete lattice Boltzmann equation (also referred to as LBGK equation due to the collision operator used).
[src:lattice-boltzmann/lattice-boltzmann-methods] We first do a 2nd-order Taylor series expansion about the left side of the LBE.
[src:lattice-boltzmann/lattice-boltzmann-methods] This is chosen over a simpler 1st-order Taylor expansion as the discrete LBE cannot be recovered.
[src:lattice-boltzmann/lattice-boltzmann-methods] By substituting the expanded equilibrium and non-equilibrium into the Taylor expansion and separating into different orders of K , the continuum equations are nearly derived.
[src:lattice-boltzmann/lattice-boltzmann-methods] The equilibrium distribution is only valid for small velocities or small Mach numbers.
[src:lattice-boltzmann/lattice-boltzmann-methods] This derivation follows the work of Chen and Doolen.
[src:lattice-boltzmann/lattice-boltzmann-methods] F is an external force, $\Omega$ is a collision integral, and ${\vec {e}}$ (also labeled by ${\vec {\xi }}$ in literature) is the microscopic velocity.
[src:lattice-boltzmann/lattice-boltzmann-methods] The external force F is related to temperature external force G by the relation below.
[src:lattice-boltzmann/lattice-boltzmann-methods] A typical test for one's model is the Rayleigh–Bénard convection for G .
[src:lattice-boltzmann/lattice-boltzmann-methods] The lattice Boltzmann method discretizes this equation by limiting space to a lattice and the velocity space to a discrete set of microscopic velocities (i. e. ${\vec {e}}_{i}=({\vec {e}}_{ix},{\vec {e}}_{iy})$ ).
[src:lattice-boltzmann/lattice-boltzmann-methods] In the collision operator $f_{i}^{\text{eq}}$ is the discrete, equilibrium particle probability distribution function.
[src:lattice-boltzmann/lattice-boltzmann-methods] In D2Q9 and D3Q19, it is shown below for an incompressible flow in continuous and discrete form where *D*, *R*, and *T* are the dimension, universal gas constant, and absolute temperature respectively.
[src:lattice-boltzmann/lattice-boltzmann-methods] The partial derivation for the continuous to discrete form is provided through a simple derivation to second order accuracy.
[src:lattice-boltzmann/lattice-boltzmann-methods] As much work has already been done on a single-component flow, the following TLBM will be discussed.
[src:lattice-boltzmann/lattice-boltzmann-methods] The multicomponent/multiphase TLBM is also more intriguing and useful than simply one component.
[src:lattice-boltzmann/lattice-boltzmann-methods] To be in line with current research, define the set of all components of the system (i. e. walls of porous media, multiple fluids/gases, etc.) $\Psi$ with elements $\sigma _{j}$ .
[src:lattice-boltzmann/lattice-boltzmann-methods] The moments of the $f_{i}\,\!$ give the local conserved quantities.
[src:lattice-boltzmann/lattice-boltzmann-methods] In the above equation for the equilibrium velocity $v^{\sigma }\,\!$ , the ${\vec {F}}^{\sigma }\,\!$ term is the interaction force between a component and the other components.
[src:lattice-boltzmann/lattice-boltzmann-methods] It is still the subject of much discussion as it is typically a tuning parameter that determines how fluid-fluid, fluid-gas, etc. interact.
[src:lattice-boltzmann/lattice-boltzmann-methods] Frank et al. list current models for this force term.
[src:lattice-boltzmann/lattice-boltzmann-methods] The commonly used derivations are Gunstensen chromodynamic model, Swift's free energy-based approach for both liquid/vapor systems and binary fluids, He's intermolecular interaction-based model, the Inamuro approach, and the Lee and Lin approach.
[src:lattice-boltzmann/lattice-boltzmann-methods] The following is the general description for ${\vec {F}}^{\sigma }\,\!$ as given by several authors.
[src:lattice-boltzmann/lattice-boltzmann-methods] $\psi ({\vec {x}})\,\!$ is the effective mass and $H({\vec {x}},{\vec {x}}')\,\!$ is Green's function representing the interparticle interaction with ${\vec {x}}'\,\!$ as the neighboring site.
[src:lattice-boltzmann/lattice-boltzmann-methods] The effective mass as proposed by Shan and Chen uses the following effective mass for a *single-component, multiphase system*.
[src:lattice-boltzmann/lattice-boltzmann-methods] The equation of state is also given under the condition of a single component and multiphase.
[src:lattice-boltzmann/lattice-boltzmann-methods] It was later shown by Yuan and Schaefer that the effective mass density needs to be changed to simulate multiphase flow more accurately.
[src:lattice-boltzmann/lattice-boltzmann-methods] They compared the Shan and Chen (SC), Carnahan-Starling (C–S), van der Waals (vdW), Redlich–Kwong (R–K), Redlich–Kwong Soave (RKS), and Peng–Robinson (P–R) EOS.
[src:lattice-boltzmann/lattice-boltzmann-methods] Their results revealed that the SC EOS was insufficient and that C–S, P–R, R–K, and RKS EOS are all more accurate in modeling multiphase flow of a single component.
[src:lattice-boltzmann/lattice-boltzmann-methods] For the popular isothermal Lattice Boltzmann methods these are the only conserved quantities.
[src:lattice-boltzmann/lattice-boltzmann-methods] Normally, the lattice Boltzmann methods is implemented on regular grids, However the use of unstructured grid can help with solving complex boundaries, unstructured grids are made of triangles or tetrahedra with variations.
[src:lattice-boltzmann/lattice-boltzmann-methods] where $w_{k}({\boldsymbol {x}})$ is wights of a linear interpolation of ${\boldsymbol {x}}$ by vertices of triangle or tetrahedra that ${\boldsymbol {x}}$ lies within.
[src:lattice-boltzmann/lattice-boltzmann-methods] During the last years, the LBM has proven to be a powerful tool for solving problems at different length and time scales.
[src:lattice-boltzmann/lattice-gas-automaton] As a cellular automaton, these models comprise a lattice, where the sites on the lattice can take a certain number of different states.
[src:lattice-boltzmann/lattice-gas-automaton] In lattice gas, the various states are particles with certain velocities.
[src:lattice-boltzmann/lattice-gas-automaton] Evolution of the simulation is done in discrete time steps.
[src:lattice-boltzmann/lattice-gas-automaton] After each time step, the state at a given site can be determined by the state of the site itself and neighboring sites, *before* the time step.
[src:lattice-boltzmann/lattice-gas-automaton] The state at each site is purely boolean.
[src:lattice-boltzmann/lattice-gas-automaton] At a given site, there either *is* or *is not* a particle moving in each direction.
[src:lattice-boltzmann/lattice-gas-automaton] At each time step, two processes are carried out, propagation and collision.
[src:lattice-boltzmann/lattice-gas-automaton] In the propagation step, each particle will move to a neighboring site determined by the velocity that particle had.
[src:lattice-boltzmann/lattice-gas-automaton] Barring any collisions, a particle with an upwards velocity will after the time step maintain that velocity, but be moved to the neighboring site above the original site.
[src:lattice-boltzmann/lattice-gas-automaton] The so-called exclusion principle prevents two or more particles from travelling on the same link in the same direction.
[src:lattice-boltzmann/lattice-gas-automaton] In the collision step, collision rules are used to determine what happens if multiple particles reach the same site.
[src:lattice-boltzmann/lattice-gas-automaton] These collision rules are required to maintain mass conservation, and conserve the total momentum; the block cellular automaton model can be used to achieve these conservation laws.
[src:lattice-boltzmann/lattice-gas-automaton] Note that the exclusion principle does not prevent two particles from travelling on the same link in *opposite* directions; when this happens, the two particles pass each other without colliding.
[src:lattice-boltzmann/lattice-gas-automaton] In papers published in 1973 and 1976, Jean Hardy, Yves Pomeau and Olivier de Pazzis introduced the first lattice Boltzmann model, which is called the HPP model after the authors.
[src:lattice-boltzmann/lattice-gas-automaton] HPP model is a two-dimensional model of fluid particle interactions.
[src:lattice-boltzmann/lattice-gas-automaton] In this model, the lattice is square, and the particles travel independently at a unit speed to the discrete time.
[src:lattice-boltzmann/lattice-gas-automaton] The particles can move to any of the four sites whose cells share a common edge.
[src:lattice-boltzmann/lattice-gas-automaton] If two particles collide head-on, for example a particle moving to the left meets a particle moving to the right, the outcome will be two particles leaving the site at right angles to the direction they came in.
[src:lattice-boltzmann/lattice-gas-automaton] The HPP model lacked rotational invariance, which made the model highly anisotropic.
[src:lattice-boltzmann/lattice-gas-automaton] This means for example, that the vortices produced by the HPP model are square-shaped.
[src:lattice-boltzmann/lattice-gas-automaton] The hexagonal grid model was first introduced in 1986, in a paper by Uriel Frisch, Brosl Hasslacher and Pomeau, and this has become known as the FHP model after its inventors.
[src:lattice-boltzmann/lattice-gas-automaton] The model has six or seven velocities, depending on which variation is used.
[src:lattice-boltzmann/lattice-gas-automaton] In any case, six of the velocities represent movement to each of the neighboring sites.
[src:lattice-boltzmann/lattice-gas-automaton] In some models (called FHP-II and FHP-III), a seventh velocity representing particles "at rest" is introduced.
[src:lattice-boltzmann/lattice-gas-automaton] The "at rest" particles do not propagate to neighboring sites, but they are capable of colliding with other particles.
[src:lattice-boltzmann/lattice-gas-automaton] The FHP-III model allows all possible collisions that conserve density and momentum.
[src:lattice-boltzmann/lattice-gas-automaton] Increasing the number of collisions raises the Reynolds number, so the FHP-II and FHP-III models can simulate less viscous flows than the six-speed FHP-I model.
[src:lattice-boltzmann/lattice-gas-automaton] The simple update rule of FHP model proceeds in two stages, chosen to conserve particle number and momentum.
[src:lattice-boltzmann/lattice-gas-automaton] The collision rules in the FHP model are not deterministic, some input situations produce two possible outcomes, and when this happens, one of them is picked at random.
[src:lattice-boltzmann/lattice-gas-automaton] Since random number generation is not possible through completely computational means, a pseudorandom process is usually chosen.
[src:lattice-boltzmann/lattice-gas-automaton] After the collision step a particle on a link is taken to be leaving the site.
[src:lattice-boltzmann/lattice-gas-automaton] If a site has two particles approaching head-on, they scatter.
[src:lattice-boltzmann/lattice-gas-automaton] A random choice is made between the two possible outgoing directions that conserve momentum.
[src:lattice-boltzmann/lattice-gas-automaton] The hexagonal grid does not suffer as large anisotropy troubles as those that plague the HPP square grid model, a fortunate fact that is not entirely obvious, and that prompted Frisch to remark that "the symmetry gods are benevolent".
[src:lattice-boltzmann/lattice-gas-automaton] For a three-dimensional grid, the only regular polytope that fills the whole space is the cube, while the only regular polytopes with a sufficiently large symmetry group are the dodecahedron and icosahedron (without the second constraint the model will suffer the same drawbacks as the HPP model).
[src:lattice-boltzmann/lattice-gas-automaton] To make a model that tackles three dimensions therefore requires an increase in the number of dimensions, such as in the 1986 model by D'Humières, Lallemand and Frisch, which employed a face-centered hypercube model.
[src:lattice-boltzmann/lattice-gas-automaton] The density at a site can be found by counting the number of particles at each site.
[src:lattice-boltzmann/lattice-gas-automaton] If the particles are multiplied with the unit velocity before being summed, one can obtain the momentum at the site.
[src:lattice-boltzmann/lattice-gas-automaton] However, calculating density, momentum, and velocity for individual sites is subject to a large amount of noise, and in practice, one would average over a larger region to obtain more reasonable results.
[src:lattice-boltzmann/lattice-gas-automaton] Ensemble averaging is often used to reduce the statistical noise further.
[src:lattice-boltzmann/lattice-gas-automaton] The main assets held by the lattice gas model are that the boolean states mean there will be exact computing without any round-off error due to floating-point precision, and that the cellular automata system makes it possible to run lattice gas automaton simulations with parallel computing.
[src:lattice-boltzmann/lattice-gas-automaton] Disadvantages of the lattice gas method include the lack of Galilean invariance, and statistical noise.
[src:lattice-boltzmann/lattice-gas-automaton] Another problem is the difficulty in expanding the model to handle three dimensional problems, requiring the use of more dimensions to maintain a sufficiently symmetric grid to tackle such issues.
[src:lattice-boltzmann/lattice-gas-automaton] Lattice-gas cellular automata have been adapted and are still widely used for modeling collective migration in biology.
[src:lattice-boltzmann/lattice-gas-automaton] Due to the active nature of biological agents, as well as the viscuous environments cells live in, momentum conservation is not required.
[src:lattice-boltzmann/lattice-gas-automaton] Furthermore, agents may die or reproduce, so mass conservation may also be absent.
[src:lattice-boltzmann/lattice-gas-automaton] During the collision step, particles reorient stochastically following a Boltzmann distribution, simulating local interaction between individuals.
